Common.LocationDescription.Common.Text:
CBRE is pleased to present Spoonbill Reserve, a 421.05 acre development opportunity, situated along the east side of U.S. 1 in Vero Beach, FL. It consists of the northern extension of Grand Harbor, an existing gated master-planned community. 
The Spoonbill Reserve project is designed to be developed in three separate phases and the approved Conceptual Planned Development (CPD) consists of: 

- 460 single-family lots
- 412 multi-family units (condos / townhomes)
- Neighborhood commercial center (maximum of 17,440 sf on an estimated 8.66 acres)

​​​​​​​The development will also include several clubhouse and recreation areas, as well as conservation, preservation, and open space areas all designed around an innovative stormwater treatment facility abutting the existing Spoonbill Marsh property to the east.

Spoonbill Marsh is a 45 acre man-made wetlands area designed and managed by Indian River County to cleanse well-water brine and enhance the natural habitat. The facility offers tour participants an easy, one-mile walk on an existing, elevated boardwalk to view the shallow marshes and associated wildlife. The existing boardwalk system within Spoonbill Marsh will be expanded by 4,100 lf in conjunction with the development of Spoonbill Reserve.

Outside of the adjacent wetlands treatment facility, there are approximately 100 miles of waterfront land in Indian River County, including 21 miles of intracoastal waterway and 23 miles of Atlantic Ocean beaches.

Spoonbill Reserve is located in Vero Beach within central, eastern Indian River County. The County encompasses approximately 497 square miles of land and is approximately 135 miles north of Miami, 190 miles south of Jacksonville, and 98 miles east of Tampa. Indian River County is bordered by Brevard County to the north, St. Lucie County to the south, and both Osceola County and Okeechobee County to the west. The City of Vero Beach is the county seat and other incorporated areas located within the county include Fellsmere, Indian River Shores, Orchid, and Sebastian.
